‘After the cool ocean freshness of the oysters, nothing is more heartwarming to the digestion than a clear and wonder- ful consommé which, incidently is a bow to tradition. It should not be a doctored consommé, but a pure essence of the Turkey, simply seasoned with the demanding flavor of the bird crisply and clearly breaking through in all its vigor. I know that many of you feel that the Turkey is a dull bird, but with the first tablespoon of this essence, I will lay odds that you will change your

mind. It is an amazingly simple soup to prepare, requiring a little bit of time and patience and practically no work. The easy recipe appears below and. this soup in its simple dignity. calls for a happy mate. Nothing would go with it better than a fine old 1830 Sercial Solera Madeira, the driest grape of them all which harmonizes with the con- sommé. This Madeira, or its equivalent, may have inspired Shakespeare to write some of his best sonnets. One must slowly savor the soup, then the wine, then the soup separately to get the maximum sensuous pleasure out of this

course.

Editor’s Note: The 1830 Sercial Solera Madeira is dramatic to the palate, still vibrant with life despite its age, and will conjure up pictures of Thomas leflerson and Andrew Jackson as you drink it. We do not have many bottles. They cost $24.00 each. As a less expen- sive alternative. we suggest the Rain water Madeira of St. Edmund Hall in the University of Oxford. which is avail- able at the astonishingly low cost of onl)

$3 79 the bottle.

“As the ‘piece de resistance,’ simple as it may sound, I know of few dishes that have the drama and rich taste sen- sensation that a properly aged Saddle of Venison, well prepared can provide especially at the Christmas dinner where we are looking for out-of-the-ordinary repast. The trick is to get good venison —and it is not easy. I know of one man who will not let you down. He is Mr. Kaufman, the proud and knowledgable proprietor of the Maryland Market at 412 Amsterdam Avenue, New York City. His phone number is LY 5-1223 and | suggest you phone and ask for him per- sonally, describing your problem and asking his advice. He is a man worth listening to. Mr. Kaufman also tells me that he delivers everywhere in the Met- ropolitan area, so even if you live in Long Island or Westchester, it will get to you provided you give enough notice. Incidentally, perfect venison does not cost much more than many of the usual meats served at home throughout the vear. See to it that the rack is tied to- sether at the end side of the loin and the fillet is left intact. In this fashion. along the top of the Saddle, you can when you have carved the long slices then invert the meat, remove the fillets. and slice those for the guests as well.

‘Tl have done a lot of experimentation for proper accompaniment to venison and, in my opinion, nothing goes better than a fine purée of chestnuts and braised romaine both perfect foils for

the meat.

“Despite the rich taste of this game meat, there is enough depth of flavor, lusciousness and richness in Chamber- tin 1952 of Paul Bouchard to meet the challenge, and in the opinion of some of mv guests. to even overcome it—no easy task for any wine! I almost forgot there should be a garniture with the ven- ison—tiny onions, braised and blended with mushrooms and bits of tried out pork. The juices—and they are elorious

-should merely be the pan juices from the roasting process itself.”

Editor’s Note: The Chambertin 1952 of Paul Bouchard is an authentic sur- vivor of the great 1952 vintage of the Cote d’Or. It is the kind of great old Burgundy that would not be easy to find in the Inns and restaurants along the vineyard road between Dijon and Lyon. Here is one of the greatest red Burgun- dies in our Armory and one of the most dramatic red wines you could possibly serve for your Christmas din- ner. In our opinion, it is a bargain at $13.25 the bottle, $143.10 the case and for those who want old Burgund) and prefer to pay less, we boldly and unhesitatingly recommend the Beaune Bressandes 1952 of Roger Duchet, the former Mavor of Beaune. The price’ only $6.99 the bottle, $75.50 the case.

FOR AMATEUR CHEFS WHO WANT TO PREPARE CREATIVE FOOD AT LOWER COST!

Simon & Schuster are about to announce the publication of a book on food preparation and the buying and serving of wines and spirits that promises to be a classic in its field. The title is “HOW TO EAT BETTER FOR LESS MONEY — AND A GUIDE TO WINES AND SPIRITS.” The co-authors are familiar to most of you. They are JAMES BEARD, considered America’s leading food authority, and SAM AARON, President of Sherry-Lehmann, Inc., the consulting editor of the Alec Waugh book “Wines and Spirits’ recently pub- lished by Time-Life Books, Inc. and wine writer for House & Garden.

The book will be dramatically illustrated by Milton Glaser, an artist who has achieved great renown on the current scene. If all goes well, their advice on how to prepare classic dishes at lower cost, and how to acquire good wines and spirits for less than you are paying now — should appear in the form of a hand- some tome at your favorite book store about Easter time in 1970. And appropriately enough, particularly in light of the title, the publishers assure us that this volume will not be too costly.
